HJR33 Enrolled
1 Enrolled, An Act,
2
3 COMMENDING DR. LEON FRAZIER ON HIS ACCOMPLISHMENTS.
4
5 WHEREAS, with great pride and special reverence, we
6 commend Dr. Leon Frazier for his many accomplishments; and
7 WHEREAS, he loved people genuinely and served others
8 selflessly and his departure leaves a void in the lives of
9 his loving family, many friends, and the community where he
10 was highly regarded; and
11 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier was born on May 16, 1932; from a
12 young age he pursued education, and it became a cornerstone
13 of his life; he earned a Bachelor of Science in Education
14 from South Carolina State College, a Master of Science in
15 Guidance and Counseling from Alabama A&M University, and a
16 Doctor of Education in Educational Psychology from Oklahoma
17 State University; he completed further graduate study in
18 Public Administration at the University of Oklahoma; and
19 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier's professional career includes
20 noted experience as a public school teacher in South
21 Carolina; civilian technical training instructor at the
22 United States Air Force Electronics Training Center in
23 Biloxi, Mississippi; and Technical Instructor Supervisor and
24 Education Specialist, respectively, at the United States
25 Army Missile School at Redstone Arsenal; and
26 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier served in many capacities in
27 higher education as a professor, vice president, and in the
28 Office of Student Affairs at Oklahoma State University and
Page 1

Office of Student Affairs at Oklahoma State University and
HJR33 Enrolled
29 Alabama A&M University; he also served as a Licensed
30 Psychologist for the State of Alabama and State Commissioner
31 of the Alabama Department of Pensions and Security; and
32 WHEREAS, he held positions of leadership with a
33 number of public service organizations, including board
34 president of the American Institute of Psychotherapy
35 Graduate School of Psychology; president of the National
36 Association of College Deans, Registrars, and Admissions
37 Officers; and member of the Governor's Advisory Council on
38 Humanitarian Services; in addition, he was a member of the
39 job development subcommittee of the Alabama Development
40 Commission and many other organizations and committees
41 serving the community in meaningful ways; and
42 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier's faith-based leadership
43 activities included serving as the Jurisdictional Executive
44 Secretary and Finance Officer of Church of God in Christ,
45 Alabama Second Jurisdiction; and Jurisdictional President of
46 the youth department for 23 years; Dr. Frazier was Project
47 Director for the founding and accreditation of the Apostolic
48 School of Ministry of North Alabama; he provided counsel to
49 many faith-based projects of churches in the Southeastern
50 United States; and
51 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier was regarded highly in the
52 communities where he resided and served; most notably are
53 the schools that are named in his honor, including the
54 Harris Home for Children and Frazier Preparatory School in
55 Uganda, which has three campuses; and
56 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier is preceded in death by his
Page 2

WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier is preceded in death by his
HJR33 Enrolled
57 wife, Irlene Sharperson Frazier; together they reared three
58 children, all of whom earned college degrees; now therefore,
59 BE IT RESOLVED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA, BOTH
60 HOUSES THEREOF CONCURRING, That we warmly commend Dr. Leon
61 Frazier for his many distinguished accomplishments, and we
62 hereby dedicate this resolution to him posthumously with
63 utmost appreciation, admiration, and regard.
